The {{nihongo|'''Miwayama Kofun cluster'''|美和山古墳群| Miwayama Kofun-gun|}} is a group of ''[[kofun]]'' [[Kofun]]s located in Ninomiya neighborhood of the city of [[Tsuyama, Okayama|Tsuyama]], [[Okayama Prefecture]], in the [[San'yō region]] of [[Japan]]. The tumuli were collectively designated a National Historic Site in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/217359|title=美和山古墳群|trans-title= Miwayama Kofun-gun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 31, 2022}}</ref>
==Background== The Miyayama Kofun cluster is located on a hill along the left bank of the Yoshii River to the west of the Tsuyama urban area. The site was initially scheduled to be razed for a housing estate in 1977, but after the discovery of the ''kofun'' cluster, a 30,000 square meter area was quickly placed under protection as a National Historic Site for preservation. Within this area are four surviving tumuli. One is a {{nihongo|''[[zenpō-kōen-fun]]''|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|2=ja|3=前方後円墳|4=ko|5=전방후원분|6=zh|7=前方後圓墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|comement=second one attempting to fix this error|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}}, which is shaped like a keyhole, having one square end and one circular end, when viewed from above. It has a length of 80 meters, making it one of the largest keyhole-shaped Kofuns in the [[Mimasaka Province|Mimasaka region]]. The three others are all {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=circular-type|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=}} ({{nihongo|''empun''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}). ''[[Fukiishi]]'' remain on some areas of the tumuli. Artifacts [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] include ''[[haniwa]]'' fragments with patterns drawn by a spatula. From these artifacts, the tumuli are believed to have been built in the 4th century. The tumuli themselves have not been excavated, so details of the [[burial chamber]]s are unknown.
Miwayama Castle was built on this site during the [[Sengoku period]] (14th to 16th centuries), and the east and west overhangs of Miwayama No. 1 are believed to be the remains of Miwayama Castle's earthen walls.
The site is maintained as a park, and is located 15 minutes on foot from [[Innoshō Station]] on the [[JR West]] [[Kishin Line]].
